    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-08-11T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-08-11T22:00:00-05:00" n="97"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d97">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.94/25: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-08-12T10:00:00+07:00"
                            >August 12, 1940—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 10:32 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>394. My 393, August 12, 9 a.m. In acknowledging the receipt of the letter of
                    August 10 from the Chinese Minister for Foreign Affairs, I said I would transmit
                    its substance as requested but suggested that such matters could be handled in a
                    more satisfactory manner <pb facs="0080" n="72" xml:id="pg_72"/> through
                    conversations and I referred to the oral message communicated by Peck<note
                        n="25" xml:id="d97fn25">Willys R. Peck, Counselor of Embassy in
                        China.</note> to Hsu Mo on July 30. This message was the gist of the
                    Department’s 124, July 20, 4 p.m. I recalled the salient points of the
                    Department’s observations, emphasized the constant contact maintained by Hu Shih
                    with officials of the American Government and expressed confidence that the
                    Ambassador would be able to give the Minister such information regarding the
                    Department’s views as the shifting circumstances might permit.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department. Repeated to Peiping. Peiping mail to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
